Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My intuition stems from the observation that while multilingual models like mBERT have made strides in cross-lingual transfer, their tokenization and representation learning are often misaligned with the linguistic realities of low-resource languages—especially those from underrepresented language families. Papers 1–3 highlight critical limitations: (1) generic tokenizers fail to capture morphological richness in low-resource varieties; (2) transfer learning is typically unidirectional or limited to fine-tuning, neglecting dynamic knowledge reuse during inference; and (3) syntactic similarity can guide better source selection, but this isn’t integrated into pretraining itself. I propose a paradigm shift: instead of treating tokenization as a preprocessing step and representation learning as a downstream task, we co-optimize them within a linguistically informed hierarchy. By structuring pretraining around subfamilies (e.g., Niger-Congo, Trans-New Guinea), we enable shared subword patterns and contextual representations to emerge organically. This differs from prior work by integrating *hierarchical linguistic structure directly into both tokenizer design and masked language modeling*, allowing for adaptive specialization without sacrificing generalization. Unlike kNN-TL’s inference-time retrieval or TOWER’s parser-specific selection, our approach modifies the foundational pretraining phase—making it broadly applicable across NLP tasks. The novelty lies in the joint optimization loop between subfamily-aware tokenizer training and MLM, guided by typological proximity.

